-- id=20: Energy Bounce-Back and Industrial Energy Self-Generation (degree 7 — highest)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Energy Bounce-Back Loan Guarantee Scheme and related self-generation incentives enable businesses to install rooftop solar, battery storage, and gas backup capacity with government-backed financing and accelerated depreciation allowances. Introduced in the 2023 Budget as a R9 billion tax incentive programme and expanded under Operation Vulindlela Phase I, the policy shifts generation responsibility partly to the private sector while Eskom''s grid is stabilised. Firms that install renewable capacity reduce their dependence on load-shedding schedules, cutting downtime costs estimated at R20 billion per month across the economy. The scheme is administered through the commercial banking sector under SARB oversight and links directly to the Electricity Regulation Amendment Act (ERA, signed August 2024), which removed the licensing threshold for embedded generation. Industrial energy users—especially in manufacturing, mining, and agriculture—are the primary beneficiaries, with the DTI tracking uptake through the industrial energy cadastre.',
  key_quote = 'R30.78 billion in private investment committed to 1,401 MW of new generation capacity reflects the scale achievable when licensing barriers are removed. — MTBPS 2025 Fiscal Framework',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / National Treasury',
  feasibility_note = 'Fiscally neutral: leverages private capital and tax expenditure rather than direct appropriation. ERA Amendment Act provides legislative base; implementation bottleneck is grid connection queue managed by NERSA.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 20;

-- id=59: Transnet Freight Rail and Port Private Sector Participation (degree 5)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'This reform opens Transnet''s freight rail network and port terminals to private operators under a concession or third-party access model, ending the integrated monopoly that has undermined SA''s logistics competitiveness. Operation Vulindlela identified Transnet''s performance collapse—container throughput at Durban fell from 2.9 million TEUs in 2016 to under 1.7 million TEUs in 2023—as a critical binding constraint on exports, especially minerals and agricultural products. The National Ports Act and the National Land Transport Act provide partial statutory basis; the Ports Regulator of South Africa (PRSA) is the relevant oversight body. The MTBPS 2025 framework aligns this reform with the R1 trillion infrastructure programme, with concessioning of specific terminals (Durban, Ngqura) as near-term targets. The Parliamentary Committee on Transport''s BRRRs repeatedly flagged Transnet''s deteriorating asset condition, skills loss, and governance failures. The Colombia 4G model—standardised risk-sharing contracts with an independent infrastructure agency—is the cited international template.',
  key_quote = 'Transnet''s container terminal productivity sits among the lowest globally, costing exporters an estimated R40 billion annually in delays and demurrage. — Parliamentary Committee on Transport, BRRR 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / Transnet / Ports Regulator',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility: legislative amendments to National Ports Act required; union resistance (SATAWU) is the principal political constraint. Operation Vulindlela Phase II has this as a priority deliverable.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 59;

-- id=45: Critical Minerals Beneficiation Strategy (degree 4)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa holds the world''s largest known reserves of platinum group metals (PGMs), manganese, chrome, and vanadium—minerals central to the global energy transition (EV batteries, fuel cells, grid storage). The Critical Minerals Beneficiation Strategy, led by the DMRE, seeks to move beyond raw ore export toward refining, alloying, and component manufacturing within SA. The strategy links to the Green Hydrogen Commercialisation roadmap (PGMs as catalyst inputs), the APDP (platinum for fuel cell vehicles), and the JET Investment Plan. Parliamentary oversight through the PC on Mineral Resources has flagged the disconnect between beneficiation ambitions and the lack of smelting and refining capacity investment since the 1990s. Fiscal context: the 2025 MTBPS notes mining royalty revenue at R14.2 billion, but downstream value addition could multiply this severalfold. The reform requires harmonisation of the Mining Charter, the MPRDA, and the Customs and Excise Act export duty regime.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s platinum group metal reserves constitute over 80% of the global total, yet the country captures less than 15% of downstream value in the PGM supply chain. — DMRE Mineral Resources Review, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / DTIC',
  feasibility_note = 'Growth impact 4/5. Feasibility constrained by energy cost (smelting is electricity-intensive) and capital requirements for industrial-scale refining. Links energy reform directly to industrial competitiveness.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 45;

-- id=57: Advanced Manufacturing Skills for the Energy Transition (degree 4)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'As South Africa''s energy mix shifts from coal to renewables, gas, and hydrogen, the engineering and technical workforce must retrain. This reform coordinates the SETAs (particularly merSETA for metals/engineering, EWSETA for energy), TVET colleges, and industry bodies to deliver artisan qualifications in solar installation, battery systems, gas reticulation, and EV maintenance. The Presidential Climate Commission''s Just Energy Transition Investment Plan (JET-IP, endorsed at COP26 and updated in 2023) earmarks R1.5 trillion over 20 years, with labour market transition as a central pillar. The BRRR analysis found that skills mismatches were the most frequently cited constraint in both the energy and manufacturing portfolio committees. The policy also intersects with the APDP Phase 3, which requires tooling and assembly skills for new vehicle platforms. Implementation relies on the SETA Reform (id=52) as a precondition—until levy fund governance improves, training pipelines remain unreliable.',
  key_quote = 'The JET-IP estimates 200,000 workers in the coal value chain face displacement by 2035; targeted reskilling programmes must begin now to avoid a skills cliff in transition sectors. — Presidential Climate Commission JET-IP, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Higher Education and Training / DHET / SETAs',
  feasibility_note = 'Fiscally neutral to low-cost: leverages existing SDL levy funds. Implementation requires SETA governance reform first. EWSETA and merSETA have existing frameworks to build on.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 57;

-- id=32: GEPF Infrastructure Investment Mandate (degree 4)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Government Employees Pension Fund (GEPF), with assets under management exceeding R2.4 trillion, is Africa''s largest pension fund. Its investment manager, the Public Investment Corporation (PIC), holds the mandate to invest in developmental infrastructure in line with South Africa''s growth needs. This reform proposes formalising an infrastructure investment sub-mandate—directing a defined portion of GEPF/PIC allocations toward domestic infrastructure projects (energy transmission, logistics, social infrastructure) through a blended finance structure that protects beneficiary returns while channelling patient capital to the R1 trillion infrastructure programme. The Parliamentary Committee on Finance''s BRRR 2023 noted the PIC''s governance recovery post-Zondo Commission and flagged the under-utilisation of the R50 billion developmental equity portfolio. Risk management frameworks must ring-fence infrastructure investments from commercial portfolio benchmarks. The GEPF Amendment Act and PIC Act provide the legislative instruments.',
  key_quote = 'The PIC manages over R2.4 trillion in assets—mobilising even 5% toward domestic infrastructure would represent R120 billion in catalytic capital unavailable from the fiscus. — PC on Finance BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / Public Investment Corporation / GEPF',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, medium feasibility. PIC governance reform (post-Zondo) is largely complete. Requires updated investment mandate agreement between GEPF board and PIC. Beneficiary consent mechanisms are legally complex.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 32;

-- id=49: Renewable Energy Grid Integration and Transmission Expansion (degree 4)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s rapid uptake of private renewable generation—accelerated by the ERA Amendment Act and REIPPP rounds 5–7—is straining a transmission grid built around centralised coal plants in Mpumalanga. The National Transmission Company of South Africa (NTCSA), legally established under the ERA but not yet financially capitalised, must invest an estimated R180 billion over 10 years in new high-voltage lines, substations, and grid-balancing technology. This reform covers: the NTCSA capitalisation plan (linked to Eskom debt relief conditions), the Grid Connection Code update, battery storage procurement under Round 1 of the Battery Energy Storage Programme (BESSP), and the Transmission Development Plan 2024–2033. The MTBPS 2025 allocates R254 billion to Eskom conditional on unbundling milestones. Parliamentary oversight has flagged that NERSA''s approval processes for transmission projects lag by 2–4 years, blocking investment. An independent transmission planning regime, modelled on UK OFGEM''s CBA methodology, is the stated reform goal.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa needs 14,000 km of new transmission lines by 2030 to integrate committed renewable capacity—a capital programme larger than Medupi and Kusile combined. — NTCSA Transmission Development Plan, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Eskom / NTCSA / NERSA / Department of Mineral Resources and Energy',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate feasibility. Capital requirement is large but partially addressed by Eskom debt relief conditions in MTBPS. NTCSA legal establishment complete; financial independence is the next step.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 49;

-- id=88: National Reading and Literacy Crisis Response Programme (degree 4)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s 2021 PIRLS results placed Grade 4 learners last among 57 participating countries, with 81% failing to reach the minimum reading proficiency benchmark. The National Reading and Literacy Crisis Response Programme, developed under the DBE''s reading strategy and funded in part through the BRRR recommendations of the PC on Basic Education, aims to deploy structured literacy programmes—phonics-based approaches such as the Early Grade Reading Assessment (EGRA) tools—across the Foundation Phase nationally. The programme requires trained reading coaches in every district, provision of graded readers in all 11 official languages, and annual learner reading assessments linked to teacher performance data. The textbook (Chapter 7 of the SA Economy) identifies chronic underfunding of foundation phase materials, inadequate mother-tongue instruction in early grades, and teacher reading competency as the binding constraints. This reform intersects with BELA Act implementation (id=86) on language policy and the NSNP reform (id=91) on nutrition-attendance-learning links.',
  key_quote = '81% of South African Grade 4 learners cannot read for meaning in any language—a human capital catastrophe that compounds every other developmental deficit. — PIRLS 2021 South Africa Country Report',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Basic Education / Provincial Education Departments',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact (5/5), moderate cost. Structured literacy programmes have strong evidence base. Implementation bottleneck is teacher training at scale and language-specific material production. BRRR 2024 recommends dedicated reading programme budget line.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 88;

-- id=108: Primary Healthcare Platform Strengthening and CHW Integration (degree 4)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s primary healthcare (PHC) platform—comprising 3,500 public health facilities plus approximately 72,000 community health workers (CHWs) deployed through the Ward-Based PHC Outreach Teams (WBPHCOT) model—is the structural foundation for NHI. This reform consolidates the CHW programme as a formal, paid tier of the health system, implements the integrated patient registration system (IPRS) across all PHC facilities, and deploys the digital health record system (HPRS) to enable continuity of care. The PEPFAR funding transition (id=105) makes CHW formalisation urgent: an estimated 15,000 CHWs employed through PEPFAR-funded NGOs face retrenchment as US funding winds down, creating a cliff in community-level HIV/TB service delivery. The PC on Health BRRRs 2022–2024 repeatedly flagged CHW contractualisation and the absence of a national employment framework as the central gap. Cost estimates: R8–12 billion annually for full CHW formalisation, partially offset by reduced hospital admissions.',
  key_quote = 'Formalising South Africa''s 72,000 community health workers as a recognised cadre of the health workforce is the single most cost-effective intervention available for the primary care platform. — PC on Health BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Health / Provincial Health Departments',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate fiscal cost. CHW Act framework under development. NHI implementation creates political window for formalisation. PEPFAR transition (2025–2027) creates urgency.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 108;

-- id=4: AfCFTA Implementation and Intra-African Trade Expansion (degree 3)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The African Continental Free Trade Area (AfCFTA), in force since 2021, creates a market of 1.4 billion people and a combined GDP of USD 3.4 trillion. For South Africa, AfCFTA offers a structural opportunity to diversify exports beyond minerals and into manufactured goods, agri-processing, and services—where SA has comparative advantages. Implementation bottlenecks include: non-tariff barriers (divergent standards, customs procedures), infrastructure deficits at border crossings, the slow ratification of AfCFTA protocols on investment, competition, and intellectual property, and the limited capacity of ITAC and SARS to process expanded trade flows. The DTIC''s AfCFTA Action Plan (2023) identifies 10 priority sectors and 47 specific NTB reduction actions. Linking to the logistics reform agenda (Transnet, PRASA), border infrastructure investment, and the Guided Trade Initiative under AfCFTA are the near-term operational priorities. The IMF estimates AfCFTA full implementation could boost SA GDP by 1.5% annually by 2035.',
  key_quote = 'If South Africa captures even half the potential gains from AfCFTA, this represents an annual GDP increment larger than any domestically achievable structural reform—but only if logistics and regulatory barriers fall. — DTIC AfCFTA Action Plan, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / ITAC / SARS / Department of International Relations and Cooperation',
  feasibility_note = 'High growth impact. Implementation is complex and multi-jurisdictional. SA chairs the AfCFTA Secretariat through 2024, providing political leverage. Logistics reform is the binding precondition.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 4;

-- id=6: Green Hydrogen Commercialisation Strategy (degree 3)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Hydrogen Society Roadmap (2021) and the Green Hydrogen Commercialisation Strategy (2023) aim to leverage the country''s exceptional solar and wind resources, its PGM reserves (platinum as electrolyser catalyst), and its existing industrial gas infrastructure to position SA as a green hydrogen exporter and domestic industrial decarbonisation leader. The strategy identifies three near-term project clusters: green hydrogen for direct reduction ironmaking in the Northern Cape (linked to ArcelorMittal SA''s decarbonisation plans), green ammonia for fertiliser production (replacing imported grey ammonia), and green hydrogen export to the EU via the SA-Germany Hydrogen Partnership (signed 2023). The Presidential Hydrogen Commission, established under Operation Vulindlela, coordinates across DMRE, DTIC, DSIT, and DBSA. Fiscal context: R2.4 billion in catalytic funding from the JETP partnerships is earmarked for hydrogen demonstration projects. The main constraint is electrolyser cost (currently USD 800–1,200/kW) and green electricity price, both declining rapidly.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa has the resource base, the PGM catalyst supply, and the coastal export infrastructure to become a leading green hydrogen economy—the question is whether regulatory and financing frameworks can be assembled before Germany and others lock in alternative suppliers. — Presidential Hydrogen Commission Roadmap, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy / DTIC / DSIT',
  feasibility_note = 'High growth impact (5/5), long-term horizon. Current electrolyser economics require blended finance to bridge to commercial scale. JETP partnerships provide catalytic capital. EU hydrogen import targets create demand signal.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 6;

-- id=25: National Treasury PPP Unit and Infrastructure Financing Reform (degree 3)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'National Treasury Regulation 16, which governs public-private partnerships, is widely regarded as the most significant bottleneck to private infrastructure investment in South Africa. Projects currently take 4–7 years from inception to financial close under the current framework—twice the duration of comparable jurisdictions. This reform proposes: creating a dedicated infrastructure transaction advisory unit within National Treasury (analogous to Colombia''s ANI, described in the SA Economy textbook Chapter 3), streamlining the three-stage feasibility and Treasury approval process into a risk-based single gateway, expanding the Infrastructure Fund''s blended finance instruments, and improving the pipeline of "bankable" projects available to institutional investors (pension funds, DFIs). The MTBPS 2025 commits R1 trillion in infrastructure spending over the medium term; achieving this requires the project preparation and PPP execution capacity that currently does not exist. The PC on Finance BRRRs 2022–2024 consistently flagged the Infrastructure Fund''s slow disbursement rate (less than 15% of committed capital deployed by 2024).',
  key_quote = 'The Infrastructure Fund has committed capital but no pipeline—without a properly resourced PPP transaction unit, the R1 trillion infrastructure programme will remain a fiscal aspiration rather than a delivery programme. — PC on Finance BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / Infrastructure Fund / DBSA',
  feasibility_note = 'High feasibility: administrative reform within National Treasury, no legislative change required. Regulatory 16 revision is within Minister of Finance''s prerogative. Quick win once political will mobilised.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 25;

-- id=99: Infrastructure Delivery Management System: Professional Project Management (degree 3)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Infrastructure Delivery Management System (IDMS), developed by National Treasury in partnership with DPWI, provides a standardised framework for managing government construction projects from inception to close-out. Despite being policy-mandated since 2015, IDMS adoption across national and provincial departments remains below 40%, contributing to the chronic project delays, cost overruns, and maintenance failures documented in parliamentary oversight. This reform requires: mandatory IDMS use for all projects above R30 million, a dedicated pool of registered professional project managers (PMs) deployed through DPWI''s Property Management Trading Entity (PMTE), digital project dashboards visible to parliamentary oversight committees, and consequence management for officials who bypass IDMS controls. The BRRR synthesis identified infrastructure project under-expenditure—returning R5–8 billion in capital budgets annually due to planning failures—as a fiscally neutral reform opportunity: better execution of existing budgets rather than more funding. CIDB (Construction Industry Development Board) registration requirements for implementing agents are the enforcement mechanism.',
  key_quote = 'Over R5 billion in infrastructure capital budgets is returned unspent each year not for lack of funding but for lack of project preparation, professional management, and supply chain capacity. — National Treasury Infrastructure Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'DPWI / National Treasury / CIDB',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, fiscally neutral. Administrative reform within existing legal framework. Main constraint is professional PM capacity—DPWI vacancy rate for engineers and PMs exceeds 35%. CIDB can expand accreditation framework.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 99;

-- id=58: Eskom Restructuring — Generation, Transmission, and Distribution Separation (degree 3)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Eskom''s unbundling into legally and operationally separate Generation, Transmission (NTCSA), and Distribution entities is the structural centrepiece of South Africa''s electricity reform. The ERA Amendment Act (2024) provides the legislative framework; the MTBPS 2025 allocates R254 billion in Eskom debt relief contingent on restructuring milestones. The National Transmission Company of South Africa (NTCSA) was legally established in 2024 but requires financial capitalisation (estimated R40–60 billion) and operational independence from Eskom Group before it can serve as a genuine independent system operator and market facilitator. Distribution remains contentious: 177 municipal distributors hold licences, but NERSA''s Electricity Distribution Industry (EDI) restructuring programme to consolidate these into Regional Electricity Distributors (REDs) has been stalled for over 15 years due to municipal revenue protection concerns. The PC on Electricity BRRRs 2022–2024 flags the NTCSA capitalisation gap and the regulatory risk of Eskom Generation retaining market dominance post-unbundling as the key governance risks.',
  key_quote = 'Eskom''s unbundling is not complete until NTCSA is financially independent, Generation faces genuine market competition, and Distribution reform removes the threat of municipal revenue collapse—three conditions none of which yet hold. — ERA Implementation Review, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Eskom / NTCSA / DMRE / NERSA',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate feasibility. Legislative base established. Financial capitalisation of NTCSA is the critical path constraint. Municipal distribution reform (EDI restructuring) remains politically blocked.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 58;

-- id=80: Port Productivity Improvement Programme (degree 3)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s commercial ports—especially Durban (Africa''s busiest container port), Cape Town, and Ngqura—have among the lowest container dwell times and vessel turnaround rates globally. The Port Productivity Improvement Programme, coordinated by the Ports Regulator and TNPA (Transnet National Ports Authority), targets: reducing average container dwell time from 7.2 days to 3 days, improving berth utilisation rates, modernising terminal operating systems (TOS), and enabling 24/7 operations. The PRSA''s Port Tariff Methodology Review (2024) introduces productivity-linked tariff adjustments. The reform is closely linked to the concession of specific terminals (Durban''s Pier 2, Ngqura) to international terminal operators under the Transnet PSP programme (id=59). MTBPS 2025 context: logistics competitiveness is identified as a top-5 priority for the Investment Conference pipeline. The World Bank''s Logistics Performance Index ranked SA 23rd in 2023—high for Africa but below peer middle-income economies—with port efficiency as the primary drag.',
  key_quote = 'Every day of excess dwell time costs the South African economy an estimated R2 billion in working capital, demurrage charges, and foregone export earnings—productivity improvement is a no-cost growth stimulus. — Ports Regulator Annual Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Transnet / Ports Regulator of South Africa / Department of Transport',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate feasibility. TNPA has approved the Port Master Plan; execution requires private terminal operator expertise. Linked directly to Transnet PSP reform (id=59).',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 80;

-- id=3: AGOA Retention and Post-AGOA Trade Diversification (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The African Growth and Opportunity Act (AGOA) provides duty-free access to the US market for approximately 1,800 South African product categories. SA''s AGOA exports—concentrated in vehicles, citrus, wine, and minerals—were valued at USD 2.8 billion in 2023. AGOA''s current authorisation expires in September 2025, and renewal on favourable terms requires SA to demonstrate compliance with eligibility criteria including market openness, worker rights, and IP protection. The AGOA Retention Strategy, led by DIRCO and DTIC, involves diplomatic engagement with the USTR, addressing US concerns about SA''s IP regulatory approach (Copyright Amendment Bill) and its non-alignment stance on Russia. Simultaneously, the Post-AGOA Diversification Strategy develops contingency plans for EU (TDCA/SADC EPA), UK (SACUM-UK EPA), and AfCFTA alternatives. The PC on Trade''s BRRR 2024 flagged both the urgency of AGOA retention and the structural dependence on preferential access as a long-term vulnerability for SA exporters.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s vehicle assembly sector employs over 100,000 workers directly dependent on AGOA-facilitated US market access—loss of preferential access would be an immediate industrial crisis. — NAAMSA/DTIC Joint Submission, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / DIRCO / ITAC',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win diplomacy track. Political sensitivity around Russia non-alignment complicates bilateral US relationship. Copyright Amendment Bill is a linked risk factor. Diversification strategy needed regardless of AGOA outcome.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 3;

-- id=9: Special Economic Zones Reform (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Special Economic Zones programme, established under the SEZ Act (2014) and administered by DTIC, encompasses 11 designated zones including Coega, OR Tambo, East London IDZ, and the embattled Nkomazi SEZ. The programme offers investors tax concessions (15% corporate tax vs 27%), customs duty relief, employment incentives, and one-stop-shop regulatory services. However, uptake has been uneven: established zones (Coega IDZ, East London IDZ) attract significant investment, while newer zones like Nkomazi remain largely unoccupied despite years of infrastructure investment and preparation. The PC on Trade BRRR 2024 cited governance failures at Nkomazi, unresolved traditional leader land disputes, and inadequate utilities as root causes. The reform proposes: rationalising the portfolio to 6–8 high-performing zones, strengthening the SEZ Advisory Board, mandating performance contracts with annual investment and job targets, and linking SEZ infrastructure investment to the IDMS framework to improve project execution. The MTBPS 2025 allocates R4.2 billion to SEZ infrastructure over the MTEF period.',
  key_quote = 'The Nkomazi SEZ received R400 million in public investment and remains non-operational five years after designation—a cautionary lesson in the difference between designating zones and creating investor-ready industrial ecosystems. — PC on Trade, Industry and Competition BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / SEZ Advisory Board',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. Legislative framework (SEZ Act) is sound. Implementation failures are governance and execution-related. Rationalisation of portfolio politically sensitive but analytically well-supported.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 9;

-- id=7: Steel and Metal Fabrication Master Plan (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Steel and Metal Fabrication Master Plan (2021–2030), developed under the DTIC Masterplans process in partnership with Arcelor Mittal SA, Columbus Stainless, and the Steel and Engineering Industries Federation of Southern Africa (SEIFSA), aims to stabilise the domestic steel industry, retain industrial capacity, and develop downstream fabrication sectors. The master plan introduces safeguard duties on steel imports (activated by ITAC in 2023), local procurement designations for public infrastructure projects, and a Steel Development Fund to support energy efficiency and competitiveness upgrades in the sector. The context is challenging: Arcelor Mittal SA announced the closure of its Longs division in 2024 (affecting 3,500 workers), citing energy costs, cheap Chinese imports, and infrastructure bottlenecks at Transnet. The Energy Bounce-Back scheme (id=20) directly addresses energy cost competitiveness for steel producers. The master plan''s success depends on simultaneous progress in energy reform, logistics, and procurement localisation, making it one of the most dependency-intensive items in the reform agenda.',
  key_quote = 'The closure of ArcelorMittal''s long steel operations would eliminate South Africa''s capacity to produce the steel sections needed for infrastructure construction—a supply chain vulnerability with national security implications. — SEIFSA Statement, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / ITAC / merSETA',
  feasibility_note = 'Growth impact 4/5. Critically dependent on energy cost reduction (id=20) and logistics improvement (id=59). Safeguard duties provide near-term protection; medium-term competitiveness requires structural cost reduction.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 7;

-- id=8: Retail-Clothing, Textile, Footwear and Leather (R-CTFL) Master Plan (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The R-CTFL Master Plan (2019–2030), a multi-party social compact between DTIC, organised labour (SACTWU), retailers (SACCI/RFI), and manufacturers, targets doubling the sector''s contribution to GDP and employment by 2030 through a combination of import controls, localisation commitments from retailers, and productivity-linked investment support. The master plan''s central mechanism is voluntary retailer commitments to source 65% of designated product categories locally by 2030 (up from 44% in 2019), facilitated by a designated products list under the Preferential Procurement Regulations. SARS anti-dumping investigations against Chinese and Bangladesh textile imports are complementary. The PC on Trade BRRRs flagged under-performance on retailer localisation commitments and noted that customs fraud (under-invoicing of imports) undermines the economic case for local procurement. The sector employs approximately 120,000 workers, concentrated in the Eastern Cape and KwaZulu-Natal.',
  key_quote = 'Retailer commitments to source 65% of designated CTFL products locally, if honoured, could sustain 50,000 additional manufacturing jobs—but compliance monitoring remains the programme''s Achilles heel. — PC on Trade, Industry and Competition BRRR, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'DTIC / SARS / ITAC',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium feasibility. Social compact framework is functional. Enforcement of localisation commitments is the key challenge—requires SARS cooperation on customs valuation and retailer audit capacity.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 8;

-- id=21: FATF Greylisting Exit — AML/CFT Legislative Package (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'In February 2023, the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) greylisted South Africa for deficiencies in its anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorism financing (CFT) frameworks. Greylisting raises the cost of international financial transactions, increases correspondent banking scrutiny, and signals governance risk to foreign investors. The AML/CFT Legislative Package includes: the General Laws (Anti-Money Laundering and Combating Terrorism Financing) Amendment Act (2022), the Financial Sector Laws Amendment Bill, and amendments to the Non-Profit Organisations Act. Implementation requires the Financial Intelligence Centre (FIC) to expand its monitoring capacity, SARS to implement beneficial ownership registers, and the NPA to demonstrate prosecution of financial crimes. The MTBPS 2025 notes progress on FATF action plan items, with SA targeting greylisting exit by October 2025. The PC on Finance BRRRs 2023–2024 track implementation progress against FATF''s 22-point action plan. Exit from the greylist would immediately improve SA''s sovereign risk profile and reduce cross-border transaction costs for exporters and the financial sector.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s FATF greylisting costs the economy an estimated R50 billion annually in higher transaction costs and lost investment flows—exit is both an urgent priority and a test of institutional reform capacity. — National Treasury FATF Progress Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / FIC / SARS / NPA / FSCA',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win: legislative package largely enacted; implementation is the constraint. FATF October 2025 reassessment is the target. Progress on beneficial ownership registers and NPA prosecution statistics are the key metrics.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 21;

-- id=23: Fiscal Consolidation and Debt Stabilisation (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s debt-to-GDP ratio reached 77.9% in 2025/26—the highest since the 1990s, following a decade of fiscal expansion driven by SOE bailouts, social wage protection, and below-target economic growth. The MTBPS 2025 marks a historic turning point: for the first time since 2008, debt is projected to stabilise rather than continue rising, supported by a primary surplus of R68.5 billion in 2025 growing to R224 billion by 2028/29. The fiscal consolidation strategy relies on: containing the public sector wage bill, reducing SOE transfer payments (contingent on restructuring progress), improving tax compliance (SARS delivered R19.3 billion above estimate in 2025), and holding the deficit on a declining path from 4.7% to 2.7% of GDP by 2028/29. Parliamentary oversight through the Standing Committee on Finance tracks quarterly compliance with the fiscal framework under the MFMA and PFMA. The zero-based budgeting pilot (2024/25) across 5 departments is a methodological innovation for identifying spending inefficiencies within existing envelopes.',
  key_quote = 'Debt stabilising at 77.9% of GDP is the first step—but stabilisation is not consolidation, and the path to 60% requires sustained reform of the public sector wage bill and SOE transfer dependency. — National Treasury MTBPS, October 2025',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / SARS',
  feasibility_note = 'Fiscally critical. Reform is underway; risk is political: public sector unions resist wage bill containment, and social grant expansion pressures exist. R19.3 billion revenue outperformance provides near-term buffer.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 23;

-- id=84: Integrated Public Transport Networks Scale-up (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s Integrated Public Transport Networks (IPTNs), funded through the Public Transport Network Grant (PTNG), represent the country''s most significant urban mobility investment since apartheid-era planning created spatially fragmented cities. Networks in Johannesburg (Rea Vaya BRT), Cape Town (MyCiTi), George, and Rustenburg are operational; a further 12 cities have approved IPTN plans at various stages of implementation. The policy challenge is integration: BRT trunk lines operate alongside subsidised bus contracts (under the GABS/Autopax frameworks), minibus taxis (the dominant mode serving 65% of users), and Metrorail (PRASA). A unified traveller (smart card) payment system, operational real-time information, and coordinated scheduling remain aspirational rather than operational in most cities. The PTNG allocation for 2025/26 is R11.6 billion, but per-km costs of BRT construction in SA (R70–120 million/km) are among the highest globally. The Minibus Taxi Formalisation (id=83) and PRASA recovery (id=76) are necessary co-investments.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa spends over R11 billion annually on public transport networks but the majority of commuters—particularly in medium-sized cities—still depend on unsubsidised minibus taxis because integrated networks do not yet reach their communities. — Department of Transport PTNG Evaluation, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Transport / Cities / PRASA',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium-term horizon. Grant mechanism is established. Integration (across operators, payment systems, and information) is the governance challenge. PRASA recovery and taxi formalisation are preconditions for meaningful network integration.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 84;

-- id=42: Electricity Regulation Amendment Act — Competitive Electricity Market (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Electricity Regulation Amendment Act (ERA), signed by President Ramaphosa in August 2024, is the foundational legislative instrument for South Africa''s electricity market liberalisation. It removes the 100 MW licensing threshold for embedded generation (enabling large-scale private solar and wind farms without Eskom contracts), establishes the legal basis for the National Transmission Company of South Africa (NTCSA) as an independent system and market operator, and creates the framework for a competitive generation market where multiple producers sell into a transparent wholesale market. Secondary legislation—including the NTCSA governance regulations, the market rules for the wholesale electricity market, and the revised Grid Connection Code—must be completed within 12 months of enactment. The PC on Electricity''s BRRR 2024 notes that 18 of 24 required secondary regulations had been gazetted by Q3 2024, with 6 outstanding items blocking full market operationalisation. NERSA''s regulatory capacity to oversee a competitive market—rather than a single monopoly—is flagged as an institutional gap.',
  key_quote = 'The ERA Amendment Act is the most significant restructuring of South Africa''s electricity sector since the 1922 Electricity Act—its implementation will determine whether the country has a competitive energy market or merely a restructured monopoly. — Energy Council of South Africa, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'DMRE / NERSA / NTCSA',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win on remaining secondary legislation. ERA enacted; 6 outstanding regulations are the critical path. NERSA capacity building for market regulation is a medium-term investment. ERA provides the blueprint; implementation determines impact.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 42;

-- id=51: TVET College Quality and Industry Relevance — Artisan Pipeline (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s 50 public Technical and Vocational Education and Training (TVET) colleges enrol approximately 700,000 students annually but produce too few industry-ready graduates: pass rates for National Certificate (Vocational) programmes average below 45%, and employer surveys consistently report that TVET graduates lack practical competencies. The Artisan Pipeline reform, championed by the DHET and the PC on Higher Education, addresses four systemic failures: inadequate workshop equipment (many colleges teach 21st-century trades on equipment from the 1980s), insufficient industry placements (the NCV requires 18 months of workplace experience, but only 35% of students secure formal placements), lecturer competency gaps (a significant share of TVET lecturers have not worked in industry), and misalignment between programme offerings and labour market demand. The SETA Reform (id=52) is a precondition: SETA discretionary grant funding for TVET-industry partnerships has been chronically under-utilized. The Construction Sector Charter and Engineering SETA (CETA and merSETA) pilot programmes provide templates for scale.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa has a 100,000-artisan deficit against National Development Plan targets—closing this gap requires transforming TVET colleges from certification factories into genuine occupational learning institutions. — DHET Artisan Strategy Review, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Higher Education and Training / SETAs / NSF',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact over medium term. Equipment recapitalisation (R3–5 billion) is the largest cost item. Industry placement expansion requires employer incentive redesign. Lecturer re-professionalization is a 5-year programme.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 51;

-- id=60: SOE Policy Impediments Reform — PFMA, BBBEE, and Procurement (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa''s State-Owned Enterprises operate under a regulatory environment—the Public Finance Management Act (PFMA), BBBEE procurement requirements, the National Treasury Regulations, and Ministerial directives—that creates structural impediments to operational efficiency and private participation. Specific reform targets include: revising Section 54 of the PFMA to reduce ministerial pre-approval requirements for commercial transactions (which delays Eskom, Transnet, and other SOE deals by months), clarifying BBBEE scorecard treatment for SOE-private joint ventures (a barrier to private sector participation in Transnet and PRASA concessions), and harmonising the Public Procurement Act (2023) with SOE-specific procurement needs. The Presidential SOE Council, chaired by the President, coordinates governance reform across the 10 major commercial SOEs. The MTBPS 2025 notes that SOE transfer payments have declined from R40 billion to R28 billion annually as restructuring conditions tighten. The textbook (Chapter 3) identifies the statutory board model (Singapore''s statutory authorities) as the structural reform that could fundamentally change SOE governance dynamics.',
  key_quote = 'Section 54 PFMA approvals for material transactions can take 6–18 months—in competitive commercial environments, this delay is existential. SOE reform begins with removing regulatory handcuffs that prevent boards from managing their businesses. — Presidential SOE Council Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / DPSA / Department of Public Enterprises',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate feasibility. PFMA Section 54 revision requires legislative amendment. BBBEE clarification for JVs is regulatory (DTI codes). Both are administratively achievable with Treasury/DPE coordination.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 60;

-- id=68: Innovation Fund Scale-up Beyond Pilot Phase (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The South African Innovation Fund (IF), established by the DSIT in 2019 as a blended finance vehicle to commercialise university and CSIR research, completed its pilot phase (R1.4 billion committed to 42 portfolio companies) in 2023. Scale-up to R5 billion by 2027—as recommended by the PC on Science and Technology BRRR 2024—requires: a permanent legislative mandate (the IF currently operates under a company structure rather than a statutory framework), co-investment from the PIC and IDC, stronger deal pipeline from universities (through the Technology Transfer Office network), and a dedicated growth-stage fund for companies that have outgrown the IF''s early-stage focus but are too small for IDC commercial finance. The DSIT''s STI Decadal Plan 2022–2032 (id=69) sets a 1.5% of GDP R&D target, and the Innovation Fund is the vehicle for translating public R&D expenditure into commercial outcomes. South Africa currently commercialises less than 4% of university patents—the OECD average is 18%.',
  key_quote = 'The Innovation Fund''s pilot demonstrated that blended public-private funding can build an investable startup ecosystem, but pilot scale is too small to shift the needle on commercialisation of SA''s R&D base. — PC on Science, Technology and Innovation BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Science, Innovation and Technology / Innovation Fund / IDC / PIC',
  feasibility_note = 'Medium-term, moderate cost. Legislative mandate formalisation is priority. PIC co-investment requires amended investment mandate. University technology transfer capacity is the pipeline constraint.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 68;

-- id=79: Freight Rail Third-Party Access and Transnet Separation (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Operation Vulindlela''s most structurally significant logistics reform is the opening of Transnet Freight Rail''s (TFR) network to third-party private operators. The Economic Regulation of Transport Act (EROT Act, 2024) creates the Transport Economic Regulator (TER) with jurisdiction over rail, port, and pipeline access pricing and conditions—the legislative prerequisite for third-party access. The first third-party access pilot, for the iron ore line to Saldanha Bay, is underway under a framework developed in 2023. Structural separation of TFR''s infrastructure (track) from operations (trains) is the medium-term target, mirroring the Eskom unbundling model. The PC on Transport BRRRs 2022–2024 document TFR''s collapse: loaded freight volumes declined from 220 million tonnes in 2012 to 145 million tonnes in 2023, with the manganese and coal export lines most severely affected. The MTBPS 2025 links rail recovery to the mining royalty revenue baseline—a direct fiscal argument for logistics reform.',
  key_quote = 'Transnet Freight Rail''s volume collapse has cost the mining sector alone over R180 billion in foregone export revenue since 2018—restoring rail performance is the fastest path to revenue recovery without new fiscal commitments. — Minerals Council SA, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Transnet / Department of Transport / Transport Economic Regulator',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact. EROT Act enacted; TER operational by end-2024. Third-party access pilot on iron ore line is the proof-of-concept. Union resistance (UNTU, SATAWU) is the execution risk.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 79;

-- id=89: STEM Teacher Development and Retention Programme (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'South Africa produced only 9,000 mathematics pass rates above 60% at Grade 12 level in 2023—an inadequate pipeline for a technology and engineering-dependent economy. The STEM teacher crisis has two dimensions: a quantity deficit (an estimated 15,000 unfilled posts in mathematics and science across public schools) and a quality deficit (many acting mathematics teachers lack subject-matter competency, particularly in rural and township schools). The STEM Teacher Development and Retention Programme proposes: bursary-for-service agreements that fund mathematics and science teacher training in exchange for 5-year deployments to high-need schools, a STEM teacher salary premium (above the ELRC collective agreement baseline) for certified specialists, revitalised subject adviser networks in districts, and partnerships with universities offering secondary mathematics teacher qualifications. The National Education Collaboration Trust (NECT) and teacher training institutions (WITSEd, STADIO) provide existing delivery platforms. Cost estimate: R2.5 billion over 5 years for 5,000 additional qualified STEM teachers.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa passes fewer students in mathematics at 60% or above each year than Finland—a country with one-twentieth of SA''s school population. The STEM teacher shortage is the human capital bottleneck behind every other skills gap. — DBE Annual Performance Report, 2023',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Basic Education / ELRC / SACE',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate cost. Salary premium requires ELRC negotiation—historically contested. Bursary-for-service framework is administratively established (FunzaLushaka Bursary Programme provides the template).',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 89;

-- id=111: Provincial Health Department Turnaround Programme (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Seven of South Africa''s nine provincial health departments received qualified audit opinions from the Auditor-General in 2023/24, reflecting persistent failures in financial management, supply chain governance, and infrastructure maintenance. The cumulative effect—medicine stockouts, equipment breakdowns, staff non-payment, and facility collapse—falls disproportionately on the 84% of South Africans dependent on public health. The Provincial Health Department Turnaround Programme (modelled on National Treasury''s Municipal Finance Improvement Programme for local government) deploys specialist financial management, supply chain, and HR teams to the three worst-performing provinces (Eastern Cape, Limpopo, North West) with a 2-year intensive support mandate. The PC on Health BRRRs 2022–2024 document the cyclical nature of provincial health crises: the same departments that were placed under Section 100 interventions in 2011–2013 are again in distress. NHI implementation (id=104) requires a stable provincial health infrastructure as its foundation—without turnaround, NHI will formalise dysfunction rather than reform it.',
  key_quote = 'Seven provincial health departments with qualified audits represent a governance failure that NHI financing alone cannot fix—without management turnaround, the public health platform will collapse under NHI demand. — Auditor-General South Africa, Health Portfolio Audit Report, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Department of Health / National Treasury / Provincial Health Departments',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, moderate cost. Turnaround team model (MFIP equivalent) is proven at local government level. Constitutional constraints on national-provincial intervention require MEC consent mechanisms. NHI creates political incentive for turnaround.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 111;

-- id=116: SEFA Mandate Refocus: Growth-Oriented SMME Finance (degree 2)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Small Enterprise Finance Agency (SEFA), a subsidiary of the IDC, provides development finance to SMMEs and cooperatives through direct loans and wholesale lending via microfinance intermediaries. Its R2.5 billion annual deployment has been criticised by the PC on Small Business Development for: over-concentration in working capital (short-term) loans rather than growth capital (equipment, premises, expansion), excessive concentration in Gauteng (55% of portfolio) relative to provincial SMME distributions, high non-performing loan rates (above 30% in several years), and insufficient linkage with the SEDA business support ecosystem. The mandate refocus reform proposes: a 40% minimum allocation to manufacturing and agro-processing (sectors with multiplier effects), dedicated provincial deployment targets aligned with the SMME policy, a non-performing loan recovery strategy that preserves lending capacity, and a blended finance partnership with the Jobs Fund to de-risk equity investments in high-growth SMMEs. The SMME Equity Fund (proposed in the 2024 Budget) would complement SEFA''s debt offering.',
  key_quote = 'SEFA deploys R2.5 billion annually but 70% goes to retail and services—sectors with limited employment multipliers. Refocusing toward manufacturing and agro-processing would double the employment impact of every rand lent. — PC on Small Business Development BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Small Enterprise Finance Agency / IDC / Department of Small Business Development',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, fiscally neutral. Mandate refocus is within SEFA''s board prerogative with ministerial direction. NPL recovery requires specialist workout team. Provincial deployment targets need incentive structure.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 116;

-- id=70: Green Hydrogen R&D and Demonstration Programme (degree 1)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Before commercial-scale green hydrogen production is viable, a technology demonstration programme is required to establish local cost curves, train a technical workforce, and prove the PGM catalyst supply chain. The DSIT''s Hydrogen South Africa (HySA) programme—established at CSIR, NWU, and UCT since 2007—provides the scientific base. This reform scales HySA into a demonstration programme: a 10 MW electrolyser at Boegoebaai (Northern Cape), a green ammonia pilot at Richards Bay, and a fuel cell bus fleet programme in Cape Town and Johannesburg. The JET Investment Plan earmarks R1.2 billion for hydrogen demonstration, and the SA-Germany Hydrogen Partnership commits €1 billion in German development finance. The DSIT''s 2024 budget included R600 million for HySA Phase 3. Unlike the broader commercialisation strategy (id=6), this reform is specifically about the R&D-to-demonstration bridge—the "valley of death" between laboratory proof-of-concept and bankable commercial project.',
  key_quote = 'South Africa''s HySA programme produces world-class PGM catalyst research but lacks the demonstration infrastructure to attract commercial investors—R1 billion in demonstration plants would unlock R30 billion in private hydrogen investment. — DSIT HySA Programme Review, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Science, Innovation and Technology / CSIR / HySA',
  feasibility_note = 'Long-term horizon. JETP partnership funding de-risks demonstration investment. R&D base (HySA) is established. Key risk is electrolyser import dependency until local manufacturing develops.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 70;

-- id=24: SARS Capacity Expansion and Revenue Recovery (degree 1, but fiscal centrality)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The South African Revenue Service''s R19.3 billion revenue outperformance in 2025 reflects the recovery from the institutional collapse of 2014–2018 under Commissioner Moyane. SARS''s new strategic plan (2024–2028) targets: expanding the tax base by 1.5 million taxpayers through enhanced third-party data integration (property, banking, motor vehicle), deploying AI-powered audit selection to increase the audit yield rate, recovering R150 billion in outstanding tax debt (the largest category being VAT refund backlogs, which also harm business cash flow), and staffing the Large Business Centre to full capacity (currently 30% vacant). The MTBPS 2025 notes that SARS''s recovery enabled the fiscal consolidation without new tax increases—making SARS capacity the single most fiscally leveraged reform in the portfolio. The PC on Finance BRRRs 2023–2024 flag transfer pricing by multinationals (estimated R60–80 billion in annual base erosion) and VAT fraud as the two largest untapped compliance opportunities.',
  key_quote = 'SARS''s R19.3 billion revenue outperformance in 2025 demonstrates that administrative reform—not new taxes—is the most powerful available fiscal instrument. Doubling the yield would close South Africa''s entire deficit gap. — MTBPS 2025 Fiscal Framework',
  responsible_department = 'South African Revenue Service / National Treasury',
  feasibility_note = 'High impact, fiscally self-funding. SARS institutional recovery largely complete. AI audit capability and Large Business Centre staffing are the immediate investment priorities. Transfer pricing enforcement requires revised OECD-aligned DTAA legislation.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 24;

-- id=35: Integrated Resource Plan 2024 — Revised Electricity Capacity Mix (fiscally central)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The Integrated Resource Plan (IRP) is South Africa''s master plan for new electricity generation capacity. The 2024 IRP update (replacing the 2019 version, which was never formally gazetted) projects capacity needs through 2030 and 2035, incorporating the dramatic cost reduction in renewables, the closure schedule for Eskom coal stations (with just energy transition commitments), the nuclear new build programme (2,500 MW at Koeberg-2 and a new site), and the growing role of gas (LNG imports under the Gas Amendment Bill) and battery storage. The MTBPS 2025 allocates R23 billion for Eskom''s Just Energy Transition programme and references the IRP 2024 as the capacity procurement roadmap for REIPPP rounds 7 and beyond. Parliamentary oversight through the PC on Electricity flags that the IRP 2024 was still not gazetted by Q1 2025—investor uncertainty about the capacity mix is cited as a constraint on renewable energy financing. The IRP directly governs the procurement pipeline for renewable energy, gas peakers, and new nuclear, making it the anchor document for the entire energy transition agenda.',
  key_quote = 'Every month of delay in gazetting the IRP 2024 represents at least R2 billion in deferred private energy investment—the cost of regulatory uncertainty in capital-intensive infrastructure sectors. — Energy Council of South Africa, Q1 2025',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Mineral Resources and Energy',
  feasibility_note = 'Quick win: gazetting is a ministerial act requiring no legislation. Political delay relates to nuclear vs. renewables balance within the ANC. MTBPS pressure and investor demand make 2025 gazetting politically important.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 35;

-- id=61: Eskom Debt Relief Conditions and Restructuring Framework (fiscal centrality)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'Eskom''s R254 billion government debt relief package (announced in the 2023 Budget and confirmed in MTBPS 2025) is the largest single contingent liability in South African fiscal history. The relief is structured as a conditional transfer: R78 billion has been transferred to Eskom annually (2024/25 and 2025/26) in exchange for progress on unbundling milestones, governance improvements, and the ring-fencing of distribution assets for future EDI restructuring. National Treasury''s Eskom Debt Relief Implementation Report (quarterly) tracks 14 conditions, including NTCSA legal establishment (achieved), reduction in irregular expenditure (partial), and the appointment of a fit-and-proper-tested board (achieved). Outstanding conditions include the financial capitalisation of NTCSA, the distribution asset transfer plan, and a credible maintenance investment programme. The PC on Finance BRRRs flag the tension between pace of relief and pace of reform—Treasury faces pressure to transfer funds while Eskom faces pressure to restructure faster than institutional capacity allows.',
  key_quote = 'R254 billion in debt relief is the state''s largest infrastructure investment in a generation—but conditions attached must be real and enforced, or the transfer becomes a bailout that entrenches dysfunction. — PC on Finance BRRR, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'National Treasury / Eskom Board / DMRE',
  feasibility_note = 'Reform is underway. Conditions compliance is the key variable. Treasury has enforcement leverage through tranche releases. Political risk: Eskom unions and municipalities resist unbundling, creating pressure on conditions.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 61;

-- id=104: NHI Phased Implementation — Credible Roadmap and Costed Financial Plan (high profile)
UPDATE policy_ideas SET
  description = 'The National Health Insurance Act (signed June 2023) establishes the legal framework for a single-payer health financing system that will pool public and private healthcare funding, contract accredited health service providers, and guarantee universal access to a defined package of services. The NHI Fund is to be operationalised in phases: Phase 1 (2023–2026) focuses on registering health users and providers, establishing governance structures, and piloting primary care contracting in selected districts. Full implementation, including mandatory enrolment and the transfer of private medical scheme members, is envisioned post-2030. Costing remains deeply contested: National Treasury estimates put the full NHI at R200–300 billion annually (current combined public and private health spending is R650 billion), but critics argue the model requires R450+ billion given expanded benefits and population. The World Bank, IMF, and rating agencies have flagged NHI fiscal risk as a sovereign concern. The PC on Health BRRRs 2023–2024 note that Phase 1 implementation is behind schedule on provider accreditation and ICT system procurement. This idea''s reform requirement is essentially: develop a credible, costed, phased implementation plan that can survive actuarial scrutiny before Phase 2 commitments are locked in.',
  key_quote = 'The NHI''s promise of universal healthcare cannot be separated from the fiscal reality: without a credible costing model and phased plan, the Fund risks becoming the largest unfunded mandate in South African history. — National Treasury NHI Costing Working Group, 2024',
  responsible_department = 'Department of Health / National Treasury / NHI Fund Board',
  feasibility_note = 'High political priority, contested fiscal feasibility. Phase 1 implementation is the credibility test. Actuarial costing and provider payment model must be resolved before Phase 2 commitments. SA Medical Association litigation adds legal uncertainty.',
  updated_at = datetime('now')
WHERE id = 104;
